 or &quot;hariH&quot; or &quot;guruH&quot; or &quot;sauH&quot;, the visarga (H) in eac=\r\nh case is a *very light* version of plain consonant &quot;h&quot;, with no vowel adde=\r\nd at the end.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nNow, the other thing is the pron=\r\nunciation of vowel &quot;au&quot; in &quot;sauH&quot;. One pronunciationis somewhat close to &quot;o=\r\n&quot; in &quot;doctor&quot;.One pronunciation is closer to &quot;avu&quot;. If you phonologically a=\r\nnalyze and experiment with the vriddhi sandhi rule (a + e =3D ai, a + o =3D=\r\n au), you will realize that the former pronunciation is closer to truth.\n=\r\n=C2=A0\nIf you formally studied linguistics and know &quot;vowel trapezium&quot;, u is=\r\n at the top of the back and o is below it. The &quot;au&quot; sound is below &quot;o&quot; and =\r\nabove &quot;a&quot; - half the way in between. The way some people pronounce it (&quot;sav=\r\nuhu&quot;), they are actually saying 3 aksharas/syllables (sa-vu-hu) for what is=\r\n supposed to be just one!\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nLike I always say,=\r\n correct pronunciation is only 1% important. Don&#39;t intentionally mis-pronou=\r\nnce when you know what is correct. However, don&#39;t worry about what you are =\r\nnot sure of and do your best. Intention, sincerity and surrender are far mo=\r\nre important than pronunciation. There may be mantras (e.g. Veda mantras) t=\r\nhat work magically just with correct pronunciation, but there is nobody now=\r\n who can pronounce them perfectly. So forget about technicalities and incul=\r\ncate sincerity and devotion.\n\n=C2=A0\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------\nAstro=\r\nlogy & Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n--------\n\n=C2=\r\n=A0\n\n\n&gt;________________________________\n&gt; From: sillylallypally &lt;sillylally=\r\npal